","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Merlin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Aron, Arye, Sura.","French, English (of Norman origin), Italian, and German; Spanish (<b>Merlín</b>): from the Old French personal name <i>Merlin</i>, from Latin <i>Merlinus</i>, a Latinized form of Welsh <i>Myrddin</i> devised by Geoffrey of Monmouth from the Welsh form of the Romano-British placename <i>Moridunum</i> ‘sea-fort’ (Carmarthen) and popularized in the Arthurian romances.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metronymic from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Merle</i>, a pet form of <i>Miryam</i> (see   Mirkin  ), with the addition of the Slavic possessive suffix <i>-in</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Marlin","meanings":["French and English: variant of   Merlin  ."]},{"name":"Mirkin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Boris, Leonid, Ekaterina, Emiliya, Georgy, Mikhail, Raisa, Semion, Sergei, Vladimir.  Jewish Isadore, Zehava.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metronymic from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Mirke</i>, a pet form of the Biblical Hebrew name <i>Miryam</i>, which is of uncertain etymology, perhaps from a word meaning ‘wished-for child’, from an Egyptian root <i>mrj</i> with the addition of the Hebrew feminine diminutive suffix <i>-am</i> (compare   Maria  ). The surname is formed with the Slavic possessive suffix <i>-in</i>."]},{"name":"Merlino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Antonio, Rocco, Aldo, Attilio, Biagio, Carlo, Carmela, Carmelo, Carmine, Ciro.","Italian:","from the Arthurian personal name <i>Merlino</i>, borrowed from French   Merlin  ."]},{"name":"Marling","meanings":["English: variant of   Merlin  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnès","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnès de Merlin was born in 1290, in France, her father, Jacques de Merlin, was 30 and her mother, de Merlin, was 25. She had at least 1 son with Guy le Mesureur."},"et":{"1290–":"1290–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1290–1350":"1290–1350","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud"," 1330":"1330","1265":"1265","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1290":"1290","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1290–":"1290–Kuollut","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1290–1350":"1290–1350","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Ku